\begin_layout Standard
As shown above in the general formulation of the problem, a distance protection
 system may not be able to differentiate between a heavy line load and a
 fault if system is stressed enough to cause such confusion.
 Several approaches have been devised to solve the problem.
 The solutions proposed can be divided into two major paths: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Detection and mitigation of cascading events in the planning stage 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Detection and mitigation of cascading events in real time operations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the planning stage, the power system operator has access to all relay
 settings and system anticipated conditions ahead of time.
 Using the loading conditions and system settings, distance protection misoperat
ion can be anticipated and thus blocked before occurrence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real time operations research path, the following research categories
 have been offered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Modification of existing distance protection system algorithms 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Proposition of new “unit protection” principles 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Proposition of wide area protection schemes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following subsections details each of these research paths and categories.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Detection and mitigation of cascading events in the planning stage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Detection-and-mitigation-of-cascading-events-in-the-planning-stage"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most Independent System Operators (ISOs) today use N-1 criterion to judge
 whether the system is safe after the removal of one line in planning stage.
 However, given that distance protection system misoperation is not triggered
 until two or three line goes out of service 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Liscouski2004,Kosterev1999,vandenberghe2004final"

\end_inset

, the distribution of power flow is hard to be taken into account in the
 planning stage as it would mean performing N-2 and N-3 contingency analysis
 which is expensive computationally.
 Thus it is increasingly hard to assess protection system capability under
 the most stressful system conditions.
 In a stressful system condition, distance protection system may not be
 able distinguish between a fault and a heavy load on the line 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horowitz2006"

\end_inset

 causing it to trip a healthy line in its third zone of protection.
 When such confusion arises, relays are designed to trip the line within
 ninety cycles 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horowitz2006"

\end_inset

.
 If this trip is false (relay misoperation) a series of cascading events
 commences and a blackout follows within seconds.
 The original philosophy of tripping a line (secure tripping) was developed
 decades ago when engineers felt that removal of a line should not cause
 system trouble since, back in the old days, system was not operated near
 the failure threshold.
 With that being said, after the 2003 blackout NERC provisions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NERC2003"

\end_inset

 mandate that distance relays should not operate under the most severe system
 condition.
 Since it is hard to assess distance protection system operation in the
 third zone, utilities responded by disabling third zone protection  altogether.
 This effectively shortened the reach of the relays which would mean that
 with certain line outages, some lines may not be provided by a backup protectio
n.
 It could be perceived as well that since the third zone is used for providing
 backup protection for adjacent lines, disabling this zone is advisable
 only if another backup protection scheme is further explained in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horowitz2006"

\end_inset

.
 However, providing another a separate hardware set for backup protection
 comes with its associated economic costs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though blackouts have hit North American and Europe and most of the
 world in the last century, the blackout of 2003 was detrimental in making
 the scientific community produce much literature about the subject, partly
 because the consequences its events had and how its events unfold.
 In the same year of 2003, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carreras"

\end_inset

 was published to pinpoint which lines can cause the system to drift to
 a blackout.
 The idea in the paper is that a probability function is defined that can
 be used in the planning stage to measure the failure probability of the
 system after certain number of lines are taken out of service sequentially.
 The system operator can issue a warning message in real time operations
 in case of the scenarios attained in the planning stage occur during operations.
 The author also showed that the probability is heavily dependent on the
 system dynamics and the operating point.
 The authors noted that the system behavior resemble the one with self-organized
 criticality, a concept that the authors explored in more detail in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carreras2004,Nedic2006"

\end_inset

.
 The model along with its own parameters has been developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Carrerasa,Dobson"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since line heavy loading has been the reason for major blackouts 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pourbeik2006"

\end_inset

, many authors have devoted considerable effort to studying these types
 of blackouts.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bao2009"

\end_inset

, the authors define an entropy quantity that can be shown by simulations
 that the system is about the brink of collapse.
 A drawback of this approach is that it depends on the DC power flow whence
 the AC power flow should be used when the system is very stressed.
 Running an AC power flow in the planning stage requires more computational
 power.
 Mitigation of cascading events in the planning stage is further explored
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Song2007"

\end_inset

, where the emphasis is on early detection of cascading events.
 The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Song2007"

\end_inset

 are proposing certain indices that can quite accurately gauge the severity
 of system conditions and the likelihood of cascades.
 An index that is used to monitor distance relays is also proposed.
 However, in practice only N-1 contingencies are studied and thus the severity
 index is chosen based on that case.
 However, if the system enters N-2 or N-3 contingencies, tuning of the “severity
” threshold will be a difficult task computationally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pahwa"

\end_inset

 proposes three solutions in the situation when the operator finds in the
 planning stage that it will be necessary to relieve a load from an overloaded
 line.
 The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Diao"

\end_inset

 proposed that controlled islanding be made to prevent overall system collapse.
 The authors train a decision tree with certain operating conditions to
 obtain the best islanding possible.
 This process needs to be done under N-1 contingency analysis.
 A drawback of this method is the fact that the tree highly depends on the
 operating system conditions and the load pattern.
 A similar approach has been provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rigatos2009"

\end_inset

 where a neural network is used instead of a decision tree.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
In summary, the authors in this section proposed new methods to mitigate
 and prevent cascading events due to distance protection system misoperation
 in case they are discovered in the planning stage.
 However, N-1 contingency criterion is used for planning stage and cascading
 events due to distance protection misoperation had historically occurred
 after N-2 and N-3 contingencies which makes discovering them in the planning
 stage a computationally challenging task due to the large search to identify
 line outages needed to pinpoint distance protection system misoperation
 and line overloads.
\end_layout

