\begin_layout Subsubsection
Modification of existing distance protection algorithms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Modification-of-existing-distance-relay-algorithms"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With zone 3 misoperation causing the 2003 blackout, several ideas have been
 proposed to mitigate and eliminate zone 3 misoperation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jonsson2003"

\end_inset

 the rate of change of voltage is used as a trip restraint to prevent distance
 protection misoperation in the real time.
 However, for the trip command to be safe, large amount of offline simulations
 need to be carried out to know the worst case rate of change of voltage.
 Additionally, given that zone 3 are activated within 90 cycles, changes
 to zone-3 time may be needed to fully detect the zone-3 misoperation with
 this method which means that checking co-ordination with nearby distance
 protection systems need to be done as well.
 Since it is hard to distinguish between evolving pre-blackout event and
 short circuit conditions using magnitude of voltage, the rate of change
 of current as well has been used along with the rate of voltage as trip
 restraint in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sharifzadeh2014"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kundu2014"

\end_inset

 synchrophasors are proposed to supervise zone-3 operation which result
 in a very robust zone-3 distance protection system.
 However, to fully take advantage of the method, strategically located PMU
 have to exist in the system which add more complexity to the system.
 Local measurements only are used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nayak2015"

\end_inset

 to achieve zone-3 tripping.
 The drawback of this method is that the fault must have significant decaying
 DC component which makes it challenging for certain fault incipient angles.
 Additionally, the paper assumes the angle between the current and the voltage
 at the relay to be more than 50 degrees as a fault indicator.
 However, it has been pointed out in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Horowitz2006"

\end_inset

 that under stressed system condition that angle may indeed exceed that
 degree with no fault on the system.
 Several other research ideas have been proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nikolaidis2016,Liu2015,Nikolaidis"

\end_inset

.
 All these ideas are based on selecting a fourth zone such that it gives
 the distance protection system alarm when the operating conditions is about
 to enter the third zone.
 However, all of them are impeded by the fact that threshold selection highly
 depends on the system configuration and operating conditions.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Garlapati2013"

\end_inset

, a non-intrusive agent to supervise zone 3 relay is proposed.
 In this scheme, agents installed at each relay are used to aid zone 3 relays.
 Since the agent in non-intrusive, it only aids the protection without enforcing
 a decision.
 A drawback of this approach is the need for agents that are disturbed in
 the system which need to communicate with each other which require high
 communication bandwidth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
In summary, valuable research has been performed to modify existing zone
 3 distance protection logic.
 However, most of the proposed modifications are based on experience with
 previous zone 3 misoperation occurrences such as the 2003 blackout.
 It is thus not entirely clear whether these methods will be able to prevent
 future distance protection misoperation if other system wide cascading
 conditions are encountered.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Proposition of new transmission line protection principles 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Proposition-of-new-unit-protection-relaying-principles"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When it comes to new single unit protection schemes, traveling wave based
 fault detection and location has been proposed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dommel1987"

\end_inset

.
 A traveling waves based protection technique using wavelets and principal
 component analysis is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jafarian2010"

\end_inset

, where a principal component analysis is used to identify dominant patterns
 of the voltage and current signal which is preprocessed by wavelet transforms.
 The proposed algorithm uses the polarity, magnitude and time interval to
 propose discrimination criteria for protection.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lopes,Lopes2013"

\end_inset

, Parks transformation is used to transform both traveling waves of voltages
 or currents at one end of the line.
 After that a rotation frame establishes whether the waveforms are due to
 a fault or not.
 The system is in steady state with no fault if the rotation frame measured
 is balanced and rotating with zero rotational speed to the predefined ABC
 frame.
 However, when a fault occurs, the measured rotation frame is different
 than the predefined ABC frame rotation causing the fault to be detected.
 In this method, it not quite possible to tell whether the fault is from
 the faulted line or due another line since the rotation is used a fault
 discriminant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fault generated waveforms varies with time and frequency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shang"

\end_inset

, so neither pure time nor pure frequency methods are suitable for such
 transient signals.
 The unique features of wavelets make them very suitable to capture specific
 period of time without analyzing other parts of the signal which is very
 different from Fourier analysis.
 Wavelet transform transfer the time domain function to time scaling function
 at different set of frequencies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Daubechies1990"

\end_inset

.
 This makes wavelets very suitable for various functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Robertson1996,Ibrahim2002,Gaouda2002,Gaouda2000,Santoso1996,Poisson2000,Moreno"

\end_inset

 in power systems using deterministic and probabilistic approaches.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Magnago1998"

\end_inset

 transforms the signals from the a-b-c frame into the modal form then applies
 the wavelet transform to the resulting voltage and current signals to detect
 the fault.
 However, the paper uses the energy of the transformed signals which is
 likely to be confused for faults on adjacent lines.
 Since there seems no relation between the energy contained in the wavelets
 and the associated transient phenomena, as the energy depends on the width
 of the window frame, various neural network papers have been devised to
 attack this problem.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jafarian2013"

\end_inset

, a high frequency transient based protection using support vector machines
 is given where appropriate line traps are installed at the terminals of
 the line and support vector machines are used to classify internal and
 external faults based on the frequency spectrum of the current signals.
 An adaptive wavelets based on Bayesian linear discrimination is given in
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perez2011"

\end_inset

.
 Only current measurement is used and is applied to windows shorter than
 one fourth of a cycle.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yadav2015"

\end_inset

, a single ended algorithm for fault detection and classification of faults
 on double circuit lines have been proposed.
 The algorithm uses both voltages and currents at a single end of the line
 to detect and classify faults.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saravanababu"

\end_inset

 three phase currents are used to detect and classify faults.
 A single stage DWT is performed with DB6 and the wavelets coefficients
 are then extracted for a windows of 0.25 seconds.
 The first coefficient to be extracted is then compared against a predetermined
 threshold which if exceeded a fault is declared.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "He2014"

\end_inset

, time domain features as well as frequency domain features are both extracted
 for one quarter of a cycle to train a rough membership neural network.
 A drawback of this approach is the massive amount of preprocessing that
 is needed to detect and classify faults.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Liu2014"

\end_inset

 Tsallis Entropy is used instead of the traditional Shannon entropy approach
 to detect and classify faults.
 It is shown in this paper that Tsallis Entropy gives better classification
 accuracy than traditionally entropy based methods.
 Additionally, it is shown that using Tsallis entropy makes it easier to
 select the threshold for fault detection.
 The authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Probert"

\end_inset

 are using wavelets to detect and classify high frequency transients as
 frequencies map to different wavelet components.
 Wavelet packets are used in [56] to detect and locate faults.
 Simply put, the paper uses packets to decompose and reconstruct high frequency
 signals generated by the fault, then the energy of the packets are compared
 to a threshold to detect faults.
 A directional ultra-fast protection based on wavelets is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duan"

\end_inset

.
 The wavelet transform spectrum energy is introduced to represent the energy
 of the high frequency components of the two components.
 These components are derived from the forward and traveling waves of the
 fault voltage and current.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Feng"

\end_inset

 gives an algorithm for distance protection using wavelets.
 The algorithm is wavelet counterpart of the DFT (discrete Fourier transform)
 used in modern day distance relays.
 However, the author does not say how his algorithm will prevent distance
 protection misoperation since after all it still uses impedance as an indicator
 for fault detection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of artificial neural networks for fault classification and detection
 has been given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dalstein1995,Kezunovic1995a,Oleskovicz2001"

\end_inset

 where voltage and current samples are fed directly to the ANN for fault
 detection and classification on the protected line.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kezunovic1995a"

\end_inset

 samples of voltages and currents are used as a feature vector to train
 ANN.
 With the advent of wavelets, special wavelets transforms are applied to
 voltage and current waveforms before they are fed to the ANN for training
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin2003,Zwe-Lee2004"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Martin2003"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Zwe-Lee2004"

\end_inset

, DWT is applied to voltage and current signals at a relay location resulting
 in series of details coefficients that are fed to the ANN for fault detection
 and type classification.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Silva2006"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mao2001"

\end_inset

, DWT is applied to voltages and currents but instead of feeding the details
 coefficients to the ANN, entropy (energy) of the signal is captured and
 fed instead to the ANN to make fault type classification between faults
 on the same transmission line.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perera2011"

\end_inset

 the energy of certain current levels and approximations is used to train
 a probabilistic classifier, and using this energy feature a decision is
 made whether a transient signal if due to a fault or non-fault condition
 on a line.
 An expert system based neural network is proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dasgupta2012"

\end_inset

 where entropy database is used for fault detection and classification.
 Since the parameters of transmission lines in reality varies stochastically
 in a specific range, the authors in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SouzaGomes2013"

\end_inset

 studied the effect of this stochastic nature of line parameters in deep
 detail.
 With the introduction of renewable energy, hybrid lines is starting to
 proliferate in the transmission system, namely lines that have both underground
 cables sections and overhead sections connected together.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Livani2014"

\end_inset

, an SVM based approach uses the first level of DWT voltage coefficients
 to detect and classify faults on these hybrid lines.
 A detailed look at literature reveals that very few attempts have been
 done to harness the power of the wavelets details coefficients alone and
 understand their underlying structure.
 
\end_layout

